ned in the config file and what's already being passed as command-line arguments. security.authorization: enabled` in config AND `--auth` on command line cause any problem? No, it should be fine.\n\nOK so the plan is:\n1. Update the configmap with the new target values:\n   - `verbosity: 2`\n   - `slowOpThresholdMs: 400`\n   - Keep `journalCompressor: zlib`\n2. Add a volume and volumeMount to the StatefulSet for the configmap\n3. Add `--config /etc/mongod/mongod.conf` to the mongod command (keeping existing flags too, since some may override config)\n4. Do a rolling restart:\n   - Restart secondaries first (one at a time)\n   - Step down primary, then restart it\n\nActually, I'm reconsidering whether I need the config file mount at all—some of these changes can be applied at runtime. The logging verbosity and slow-operation threshold can be adjusted with runtime commands, but the journal compression switch requires a restart anyway, so I might as well use the config file approach for all three changes.\n\nFor WiredTiger journal compression specifically, the journal file format is set at startup and can't be reconfigured at runtime through `wiredTigerEngineRuntimeConfig`. So I definitely need the config file mount and a rolling restart to apply that change.\n\nNow I'm ready to write the code for this solution. With 3 members, the other replicas can elect a new primary if pod-0 goes down, so the cluster stays available during the election window. I could manually step down the primary before the StatefulSet restart reaches it, but that's unnecessarily complex—letting Kubernetes handle the rolling restart is simpler and maintains quorum throughout. So I'm weighing a config file approach with a StatefulSet update against a runtime-only approach.\n\nThe problem is WiredTiger settings can't be changed at runtime, and the task requires the zlib compression to be \"applied consistently across all members\"—meaning it needs to actually be in effect, not just sitting in an un